From: Cauldron <cauldron@cauldron.app>
Date: Mon, 7 Apr 2026
Subject: [PATCH] ntdll: Prefer native DLLs from application directory over builtins

When a PE DLL exists in the application directory (e.g. d3d11.dll from
DXMT/DXVK), prefer it over Wine's builtin version. This allows graphics
translation layers to work reliably when their DLLs are placed in the
game directory, without requiring WINEDLLOVERRIDES environment variable.

This is critical for games launched through Steam's -applaunch, where
the Unix process environment from the initial wine launch does not
propagate to child game processes.

Wine-Bug: https://bugs.winehq.org/show_bug.cgi?id=0
---
 dlls/ntdll/unix/loadorder.c | 24 ++++++++++++++++++++++++
 1 file changed, 24 insertions(+)

diff --git a/dlls/ntdll/unix/loadorder.c b/dlls/ntdll/unix/loadorder.c
index 1234567..abcdefg 100644
--- a/dlls/ntdll/unix/loadorder.c
+++ b/dlls/ntdll/unix/loadorder.c
@@ -511,6 +511,30 @@ enum loadorder get_load_order( const UNICODE_STRING *nt_name, BOOL is_system_dir
         goto done;

     /* now some heuristics for explicit paths */
+
+    /* Cauldron: If a non-builtin PE DLL exists in the application directory
+     * for a known graphics DLL (d3d11, dxgi, d3d10core, d3d12, d3d9),
+     * prefer native,builtin loading. This enables DXMT/DXVK/vkd3d-proton
+     * to work by simply placing DLLs in the game directory. */
+    if (!is_system_dir && pe_mapping && pe_mapping)
+    {
+        static const WCHAR *graphics_dlls[] = {
+            L"d3d11", L"d3d10core", L"d3d9", L"d3d12", L"dxgi", NULL
+        };
+        const WCHAR **gfx;
+        for (gfx = graphics_dlls; *gfx; gfx++)
+        {
+            if (!wcsicmp( basename, *gfx ))
+            {
+                /* Found a graphics DLL in app dir — prefer native */
+                ret = LO_NATIVE_BUILTIN;
+                TRACE( "got cauldron app-dir native %s for %s\n",
+                       debugstr_loadorder(ret), debugstr_us(nt_name) );
+                goto done;
+            }
+        }
+    }
+
     if (!is_system_dir)
     {
         /* module basename without '*' */
